{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01KKD9LG771KmPJU1LT9f26k","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see it now. `ucl_skip_comments` only skips comments (lines starting with `#` or blocks starting with `/*`). It does NOT skip leading whitespace.\n\nIn `UCL_STATE_INIT`:\n```c\nif (!ucl_skip_comments (parser)) { ... }\nelse {\n    p = chunk->pos;\n    if (*p == '[') {\n        parser->state = UCL_STATE_VALUE;\n        ucl_chunk_skipc (chunk, p);\n    }\n    else {\n        parser->state = UCL_STATE_KEY;\n        if (*p == '{') {\n\n\n```\n\nContinuing with the rest of the conditional...\n\nSo with the input `\\n\\n   {\\\"key\\\": \\\"value\\\"}\\n`, after `ucl_skip_comments` returns without doing anything, `p` points to the first newline. Since `*p` is `\\n` rather than `[` or `{`, we enter the else branch, set the state to `UCL_STATE_KEY`, and skip nothing. Then in `UCL_STATE_KEY`, the parser checks what character we're at to determine how to proceed.\n\nNow we're skipping whitespace characters and checking for special cases like `}` or an empty stack. After skipping the newlines and spaces, `p` points to `{`, and we call `ucl_parse_key`. But in `ucl_parse_key`, the `{` character doesn't match any of the expected conditions for a valid key start—it's not a comment, not whitespace, and doesn't have the `UCL_CHARACTER_KEY_START` flag set, so the parser will likely hit an error condition or fall through to handle this as an invalid key.\n\nLooking back at `UCL_STATE_INIT`, I think I see the real issue now: when there's leading whitespace before the opening `{`, the state doesn't skip that whitespace first, so it ends up taking the wrong branch and transitioning to `UCL_STATE_KEY` instead of properly recognizing the `{` as the start of an object.\n\nThen in `UCL_STATE_KEY`, the parser does skip whitespace and eventually encounters the `{`, but at that point it's already in the wrong state and tries to parse it as a key instead of handling it as an object delimiter.\n\nThe real problem is that `UCL_STATE_INIT` needs to skip leading whitespace before checking what the first non-whitespace character is. The fix would be to add whitespace-skipping logic at the beginning of the `UCL_STATE_INIT` case, so it properly detects whether the input starts with `[` or `{` regardless of leading spaces. I see the issue now—the comment claims to skip spaces, but the code doesn't actually do that. It just checks if the current character is `[` or `{` without consuming any leading whitespace first, so when there's whitespace before the opening brace, the parser gets confused about what state it should enter. I'm looking back at the exact section around lines 1663-1675 in the `UCL_STATE_INIT` handler to verify where the whitespace-skipping logic is missing and confirm this is what's causing the parser to choke on leading whitespace before the opening brace or bracket.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":763,"cache_read_input_tokens":43639,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":763},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"738e3405-02e2-43f7-b396-8141f9d90a30","uuid":"94e172f6-410f-4032-82d7-8b1f3e55aa7c"}
